{
  "doc_id": "26803",
  "text": "The second key issue results from pressure ulcers being a consequence of reduced mobility that maybe caused by a large number of diseases, medical interventions and comorbidities [CITATION_1] . Any disease or intervention that results in the patient being immobile or unable to change their own position for long periods puts the patient at risk of developing a pressure ulcer. Examples highlighted include: having surgery [CITATION_2] , dementia/cognitively impairment [CITATION_3] , stroke or neurological disease [CITATION_4] , spinal injury [CITATION_5] , diabetes [CITATION_6] , malnutrition [CITATION_7] and even faecal incontinence [CITATION_8] [CITATION_9] . Therefore there may be the potential for any impact of pressure ulceration to be masked by the diversity and range of potential causes of pressure ulcers.",
